Section 4.		ACUPUNCTURE - A NEW OLD TRADITION
				Christopher C. Browne

Christopher Browne is a certified Doctor of Acupuncture. His studies 
were conducted at Colombo South General Hospital, Sri Lanka (known as 
the largest and best teaching facility in the world of Acupuncture). 
He has acquired a D.AC., Ph.D in Acupuncture and is one of 4 C.A.P.'s
(Certified Addiction Professional) in Canada. Among other associations, 
he is a founder member of the Comonwealth Institute of Acupuncture & 
Natural Medicines. Christopher Browne accepts appointments at 
117 Grand Ave, London, Ontario, N6C 1L9 and can be reached at 
(519)439-0854.

	In North America, one of the most highly industrialized societies 
in the world, people are enjoying a very affluent lifestyle, free of the 
life depravities common in many developing countries. However, millions 
of people suffer from various kinds of non-infectious, chronic, 
constitutional and aging induced degenerative ailments. Our intense
industrialization and urbanization have produced a very complicated 
competitive and fast moving society which produces constant emotional 
and mental strain or "stress". How to cope with stress related ailments
effectively is fast becoming our main concern.

	Today, more and more people are seeking alternative therapies. 
This trend has been very conscious over the past two decades. In 1972, 
the news of Acupuncture Anesthesia from China surged all over the world. 
This focused attention on oriental medicine has been practiced as a 
genuine medicine in China and other far eastern countries for the past 
three thousand years. Today, more and more western medical professionals 
have started studying and practicing Acupuncture. The demand has been
increasing yearly.

The World Health Organization has adopted Acupuncture, moxibustion and 
Chinese Herbology as an alternative medicine. It has been actively 
promoting its understanding and development all over the world.

Oriental medicine is growing in popularity steadily in spite of its 
rather unintelligible science, for these reasons:

1. It is an empirical medicine which has been developed, and systemized,
and has survived for 3,000 years among Asian people.

2. It is effective for non-infectious, chronic, constitutional and 
degenerative disorders and stress-related ailments, which have not been
adequately coped with by conventional medicine.

3. It is based on a philosophy that the human being is part of nature; 
our body is controlled by the universal law (Natural Law); therefore we 
have to live in harmony with nature as much as possible. This philosophy
matches the demands of modern people who have been deprived of living in
harmony with nature because of the rapid urbanization and it's artificial
environment.

4. It emphasizes the holistic approach towards ailments and the diseased
person; the patient is treated just as a whole being with union of body, 
mind and spirit, instead of being treated as a diseased body. The 
therapist's relationship towards the patient is emphatic, personal and 
close.

5. It is very natural, safe and has virtually no side effects. The most
commonly accepted theory is the "Nerve-reflex Theory". It holds that 
when abnormal conditions occur in an internal organ, alterations take 
place in the skin and muscle related to that organ via the nervous system. 
The nervous system extending through the internal organs, the skin and 
the subcutaneous tissue and muscles, constantly transmit information about 
the physical condition to the spinal cord and the brain. These information 
impulses set up a reflex action that cause symptoms of internal organic
disorders to manifest themselves on the surface areas of the body as
hypersensitivity or hyposensitivity, spasm, contraction, tightness or 
lumping of the muscles, discolouration, dryness or oiliness of the skin, 
etc. At the same time, the ultimate relation of the internal organs and
external ones has the reverse effect too. I.e. stimulation on the skin 
and the muscles from the outside are transmitted to the inside via the 
nervous system.

	It is in these areas that Acupuncture and moxibustion has 
utilized this relationship to its advantage. In fact it has been 
scientifically verified that Acupuncture and moxibustion can cause 
dilation of the vessels and increase the overall blood and lymph 
circulation, increase the production of blood cells, activate the 
hormone secretion and immune system, relax the contracted or spastic 
muscles etc. It is now believed that Acupuncture releases endorphins. 
Bruce Pomeranzs M.D. (McGill), Ph.D. (Harvard), Professor of 
Neurobiology, University of Toronto, Ontario, Canada pioneer scientific 
worker on the Endorphin Mechanism found that it is by this mechanism 
that Acupuncture has it's analgesic effect.

	Medical professionals as well as the public in our western 
countries are conditioned to believe that Oriental medicine, especially
Acupuncture can be effective only for "pain relief". However, in the 
Asian and some European countries these treatments have been applied to 
almost every kind of ailment and the public are more aware of its merits 
and demerits.

	Popular belief is that Oriental medicine is more effective for 
non-infectious, chronic, constitutional and aging induced diseases, 
while Western medicine is very effective for acute, infectious and 
mechanical disorders. The World Health Organization has put forward a 
similar list of disorders, which lend themselves to Oriental medicines. 
>From my clinical experiences, the most commonly treatable ailments by
