Section 5.			CHOICE TIDBITS

The Facts on Flaxseed

	Flaxseed has emerged as food with potential disease-fighting 
power and the national Cancer Institute is currently studying its 
possible health benefits, reports Environmental Nutrition (August 1995).
	"The renewed interest in flax has been fueled by its possible link 
to preventing cancer. Flaxseeds are an important source of lignins, plant
compounds that provide fiber and exhibit anti-cancer properties. In 
humans, cancers of the breast, colon and prostate are cited as most 
likely to be thwarted by lignins, but more studies are needed."
	The report continues, "Flaxseed is a rich source of alphalinolenic 
acid, and essential fatty acid the body can convert into omega 3 fatty 
acids. Research has indicated that omega 3 has been shown to keep blood
platelets from sticking together and building up on artery walls."
			(Let's Live, April 1996)

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Antioxidant Interactions

	"Epidemiologist Paul Jacques and his colleagues at the Human 
Nutrition Research Center on Aging at Tufts University, gathered diet
information and blood samples from 680 elderly people to find out how
antioxidants interact. The researchers separated people by how much 
vitamin C and carotenoids - a family of antioxidants in fruits and 
vegetables - they were getting from food. They also asked whether the
volunteers were taking vitamin E supplements. Then the scientists 
checked blood smples to see whether participants who were getting a 
lot of one vitamin had higher levels of the others.
	Vitamin C came out on top, providing the strongest protection 
to the other vitamins:  The group who got the most vitamin C from 
their diet (more than 220 milligrams a day, or roughly the amount in 
four oranges) had, on an average, 18 percent more vitamin E in their 
blood than people with the lowest intake of C (below 120 mg a day). 
Similarly, carotenoid levels jumped 13 percent for the high-C group.
	Meanwhile, those who got the most carotenoids (more than 5.5 mg 
a day, or what you'd get from three to five servings of a colorful mix 
of vegetables) had six percent more vitamin E in their blood. The people 
who got more than 30 mg a day of vitamin E had seven percent more 
vitamin C… Because people with highest intake of vitamin C received the 
most benefits, it's worth ensuring that you get at least 220 mg a day.
			(Health, May/June 1996)

